{"actual_usd":0.158015,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":318,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30649,"reply":"\"I don't think so.\" *I rest a thumb in the crease of my worn Bible and glance across the bright square a moment, the morning light catching on my white tie.* \"If all they meant was, ‘we felt changed’ or ‘we had a powerful vision,’ they could've said that. What they proclaimed was that Jesus had been raised — really, bodily, in history.\"\n\n*I shift on the bench, hearing a kayak bump softly against the dock stones beyond the bridge.* \"Christianity hangs an awful lot on that. Paul says if Christ has not been raised, our faith is vain. Not ‘if the disciples didn't have a meaningful spiritual experience’ — if Christ was not raised.\"\n\n\"Now, sure, people do have visions. Scripture knows that. But the resurrection accounts are stubbornly earthy — eating, speaking, being seen, wounds touched, people startled because they are not expecting a metaphor.\" *I give a small shrug.* \"A merely inward resurrection might inspire for a season. It would not explain that kind of witness, or the way they staked everything on a claim that could be checked, denied, punished, or killed for.\"\n\n*I look back at you with a gentler expression.* \"If Christ only rose in their hearts, then death still keeps its old throne. If he rose in the flesh, then death has been broken in the real world, not just reinterpreted. That's the Christian claim.\"\n\n\"What’s pressing on that question for you — history, theology, or the kind of thing you can still honestly believe?\"","rolling_24h_usd":82.99766,"run_id":"a4b95fc5-9788-4bd0-bf81-42e407963b10"}
